[normal]David Lawton[bold], Director of Markets, Financial Conduct Authority, gave evidence.
[normal]Chair:[bold] Good morning and thank you for agreeing to answer our questions today.
[normal] 
[normal]We know who you are but, just for voice transcription purposes, if you could, just introduce yourself.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Of course, Chairman.
[normal] 
[normal]Good morning
[normal], m
[normal]y name is David Lawton
[normal] and 
[normal]I am the Director of Markets at the Financial Conduct Authority.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q122 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Thanks very much.
[normal] 
[normal]A couple of fairly general questions to open 
[normal]with.
[normal] 
[normal]C
[normal]an you explain to the Committee the difference between headquartering and listing?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: A company that is headquartered in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] typically would be formed under the UK Companies Act.
[normal] 
[normal]That is a piece of legislation that deals with 
[normal]a
[normal] company’s constitution and how it operates.
[normal] L
[normal]isting is a generic term; we might get on to talking about some of the 
[normal]nuances of what it means a bit later
[normal], but e
[normal]ssentially it is 
[normal]about
[normal] access to capital markets.
[normal] 
[normal]People typically talk about “a UK
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]listed
[normal] company” as being a company that has access to capital markets via being traded on a 
[normal]UK
[normal] exchange.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q123 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] How significant would you say the LSE is compared with other listing platforms?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: It is by far the dominant 
[normal]UK
[normal] listed platform.
[normal] 
[normal]There are four exchanges that, under the FCA’s rules, are able to operate a listed market, and the LSE accounts for the vast majority of listed securities that are traded.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q124 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] What makes it so dominant, do you think?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: It is partly a question of history
[normal]: h
[normal]istorically, it was the only 
[normal]UK
[normal] market for trading securities and therefore has benefited from that legacy of history.
[normal] 
[normal]Secondly, the nature of markets is that liquidity begets liquidity
[normal]—
[normal]they are network
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]type
[normal] arrangements
[normal]—and i
[normal]ssuers and investors are attracted to marketplaces where there is market depth.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q125 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] What does a company have to do to be listed here in 
[normal]London
[normal], on the FTSE and the AIM?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Th
[normal]is
[normal] might be a moment just to describe a little bit more carefully what “listed” means.
[normal] 
[normal]Strictly speaking, the Official List is a list of securities that meet certain criteria set by us.
[normal] 
[normal]Separately, exchanges offer marketplaces for the trading of securities.
[normal] 
[normal]As we have talked about already, the LSE offers the largest market for the trading of listed securities.
[normal] 
[normal]AIM is a junior market operated by the LSE and, in fact, is for unlisted securities, so securities that are traded on AIM are not on the Official List. 
[normal] In order to be listed, an issuer would have to take a number of steps.
[normal] 
[normal]The first is, typically, it would have to appoint some advisers to work with it to prepare it to go through the process.
[normal] 
[normal]If an issuer wanted to be on the premium segment of the Official List—I can talk a bit more about what that means in due course—it would also have to appoint a sponsor, typically an investment bank, to co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordinate the process. It would have to produce a prospectus, which sets out details about the company, its business plan, its revenue expectations and so on, in order to provide investors with all the information that they need to make an informed assessment about the pricing of the security, and then it would need to apply to us for admission to the List and satisfy the admission criteria.
[normal] 
[normal]In parallel, it would also need to apply to an exchange to be admitted to trading.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q126 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Just going back to your comments about AIM, if it is not listed—forgive my layman’s ignorance on this—how can its shares be traded?
[normal] How would
[normal] would-be investors know how to trade with them or know that they are there to be traded?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Exchanges offer different types of market.
[normal] 
[normal]There are the listed markets that we have talked about, which obviously have strong symbiosis with the Official List that we run but, under European legislation exchanges are also able to operate junior markets in unlisted but still transferrable securities.
[normal] 
[normal]It is the nature of the securities that makes them 
[normal]tradeable
[normal], but they are not on our Official List.
[normal]Chair:[bold] I still do not understand from what you have said how somebody knows that they can trade that company’s stock.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: AIM has its own rules that govern the admission of securities to that market, and there are rules for issuers as well as for the trading.
[normal] 
[normal]The structure of those rules actually more broadly mirrors the structure of the listing regime, but the details are set by the London Stock Exchange.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q127 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Good morning, Mr Lawton.
[normal] 
[normal]I would like to ask you a couple of factual questions regarding the listing of ENRC.
[normal] 
[normal]I am not going to ask you about the investigation currently under way, because obviously that would be improper, but it would be helpful for this Committee to have a number of factual questions answered.
[normal] 
[normal]Could you confirm who was the sponsor for ENRC when they were listed?
[normal] 
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: I am afraid I do not have that information to hand, but it will have had a sponsor.
[normal] 
[normal]I can certainly let the Committee know.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q128 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] You can confirm that.
[normal] 
[normal]Thank you very much.
[normal] 
[normal]Can you confirm whether it is your intention at the FCA to review the process of how this company was listed, given the nature of the allegations that are currently before it?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: We have had an extensive dialogue with investors and other market participants over the last couple of years looking at the lessons that we can learn from the experiences of a number of companies admitted to the List.
[normal] 
[normal]We have published a package of policy proposals to change the regime to strengthen in particular the protections offered to minority shareholders, including: requiring companies that have a controlling shareholder to have a separate vote of the minority shareholders for the independent directors; requiring such companies to enter into a shareholder agreement with the major shareholders, with sanctions if it is not properly kept; and changing the rules for delisting a company.
[normal] 
[normal]I would say that we have already reviewed that process and proposed a package, which we put out for consultation three or four weeks ago, to strengthen the regime in those respects.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q129 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] On the issue of delisting, can you tell the Committee today why ENRC was allowed to delist, given it is under a Serious Fraud Office investigation at the moment?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: The shareholders voted for a delisting
[normal].
[normal] There is no connection between the ability of the SFO to pursue its enquiries and whether or not a company is on the list.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q130 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] You have no powers currently to in any way stop that company going through that process during an investigation.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: The shareholders have voted to accept the deal that is on the table, which included delisting, and the SFO investigation is separate from that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q131 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Could you, just for the purposes of today, confirm if your proposals on delisting, which you have just referred to, would change that situation in any way?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: 
[normal]To be clear, t
[normal]he current requirement is that 75% of the shareholders vote in favour of a proposal to delist.
[normal] 
[normal]Our proposal is that the minority shareholders, as a class, also 
[normal]have to vote in favour.
[normal] 
[normal]As it happens, with the vote in respect of ENRC, the minority shareholders as a class did vote in favour of a delisting.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q132 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] The proposals would not affect this particular situation occurring.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: It would give the minority shareholders as a class a separate say.
[normal] 
[normal]As it happened in relation to this particular vote, the minority shareholders as a class did vote in favour of the delisting.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q133 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] I wish to follow on 
[normal]on
[normal] the purchase of ENRC and its listing.
[normal] 
[normal]ENRC listed in December 2007 and immediately went into the FTSE
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]100.
[normal] 
