[normal]David Lawton[bold]: I am afraid I cannot confirm—
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q134 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] I would like you to confirm it, Mr Lawton.
[normal] 
[normal]You will write to us and confirm it or otherwise.
[normal] 
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Of course.
[normal] 
[normal]What I meant, Mr
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Binley, is I am not aware whether we did or not, but I will certainly confirm.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q135 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] You are not aware of it—an issue of that importance?
[normal] 
[normal]Somebody comes in, goes straight into the FTSE on your say
[normal]-
[normal]so, and you were not aware that, three months before, a serious report was written questioning their operating systems in terms of fraudulent behaviour.
[normal] 
[normal]You were not aware of that?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: In order to become a premium listed company, companies have to comply with our admission criteria, which include confirmation from the sponsor that a company meets our rules and, on a forward
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]looking basis, is capable of meeting the rules.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q136 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] You are saying, Mr Lawton, that if a respected auditor had made a report three months before this company was listed, you would take no notice of that report.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: No, I am not saying that.
[normal] 
[normal]It is an important feature of our regime that companies that are listed are not doing so in a way that enables the 
[normal]UK
[normal] financial system to be used for a purpose connected to financial crime.
[normal] 
[normal]It is one of our statutory objectives to make sure that that does not happen.
[normal] 
[normal]All that type of information needs to be assessed, both by the FCA and by the sponsor, to make sure that a company applying for admission to the Official List, particularly a premium listed company, meets those criteria.
[normal] 
[normal]What I am just saying specifically in relation to your question, and I certainly will of course confirm for the Committee, is that I am afraid I am not aware of the Herbert Smith report personally.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q137 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] You are the protector of the probity of our Stock Exchange, are you not?
[normal] 
[normal]That is your role.
[normal] 
[normal]You protect investors from companies that would use our structures to defraud people.
[normal] 
[normal]Right?
[normal] 
[normal]That is your prime role.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Absolutely
[normal], it is certainly—
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q138 [bold]&#xa0; 
