[normal] 
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: In relation to the SFO investigation, we will have to wait and see how that concludes.
[normal] 
[normal]In relation to the admission to the List, in relation to your direct question, it certainly was the case that the FCA, confirmed by attestation from sponsors, felt that this company met the admission criteria.
[normal]Chair:[bold] We are going to talk about the issue of sponsors in one moment.
[normal] 
[normal]Can I bring in Ann 
[normal]McKechin
[normal] on broader issues?
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q143 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Just on one final point: when you confirm to us the name of the sponsor, can you provide us, given that this company is now delisted, with a copy of the report that the sponsors provided to you in relation to that company?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: If that is something that I can do, I will certainly satisfy the Committee on that.
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] I think it will be very important to the Committee to examine that report.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: I just need to make sure that there are no confidentiality concerns about that but, subject to that, yes, of course.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q144 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Thank you, Mr Lawton.
[normal] 
[normal]That is very helpful.
[normal] 
[normal]Can I just go on to more general questions?
[normal] 
[normal]You mentioned in your written evidence that mineral companies have slightly modified admission criteria
[normal]—i
[normal]n fact, considerably less than for companies that are not in this sector.
[normal] 
[normal]Could you run through why there are different premium criteria for these companies?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Yes indeed.
[normal] 
[normal]It is largely due to the technical nature of the industry.
[normal] 
[normal]It is certainly not the case that the different criteria imply a lesser standard.
[normal] 
[normal]For the premium listed company, a normal company would need to have what is called a three
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]year track record, in other words be able to demonstrate three years of ongoing business
[normal],
[normal] properly audited.
[normal] 
[normal]In relation to mineral companies, the thing that investors particularly focus on is an independent expert’s report on the reserves and mineral assets that they have access to, so that takes the place of the three
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]year track record.
[normal] 
[normal]The other criterion that applies to a normal company is that you have to have control of the business.
[normal] 
[normal]In relation to the mineral sector, a typical business practice might be to have co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]investments
[normal] or production
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]sharing
[normal] arrangements.
[normal] 
[normal]Therefore, for that type of company, we do not insist that you have control of your business, but we simply insist that you have a range of such investments.
[normal] 
[normal]Those two differences really just reflect the technical nature of the minerals sector.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q145 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Is the report from the sponsor any different for a mineral company from what it would be for a non
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]mineral
[normal] company?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: No.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q146 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] If you are entering into co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]partnership with other partners as alliances, surely that might necessitate further investigation and a more thorough investigation to ensure that the company’s activities are such that they are not going to bring the listing into disrepute.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: There are two important steps in relation to this admission process.
[normal] 
[normal]The first is that the prospectus that we talked about earlier clearly has to disclose all the relevant information about the company and its investment prospects, including the details of any production
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]sharing
[normal] arrangements and so on.
[normal] 
[normal]Regarding the sponsor’s due diligence, when I said that the sponsor’s report is the same, the attestations that they make and the questions they answer are the same but, of course, in relation to a particular company’s circumstances, the amount of due diligence and the areas that need to be probed in order to be able to reach those attestations may be different.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q147 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] The sponsor is presumably paid a fee to carry out the due diligence and essentially vouch for a company.
[normal] 
[normal]How do you tackle the inevitable conflict of interest if the investment company is also in effect an agent for the company concerned?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Sponsors really have two sets of responsibilities.
[normal] 
[normal]Under our regime, they are supervised by us and authorised by us to perform the sponsor activity, and we do quite a lot of supervision of the sponsor activity in relation to those firms.
[normal] 
[normal]Where we feel that the sponsor is not acting in accordance with what we want, then we have the ability to take action including discipline.
[normal] 
[normal]The second responsibility is the one that you have just mentioned, which is facing off to the issuer.
[normal] 
[normal]Sponsors have that dual responsibility.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q148 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Has any company faced discipline?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Yes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q149 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Have any companies been barred from being sponsors?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: The new Financial Services and Markets Act, which came into effect in April of this year, has strengthened our ability to both restrict the range of areas where a sponsor could offer services, if we felt that was necessary, but also to suspend a sponsor’s activity and ultimately take them off the list.
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Which you had not had previously.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Which we did not have previously; that is right.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q150 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Have you considered the argument for insisting that sponsors be independent from the applicant companies themselves, particularly if much of their activity is actually 
[normal]outwith
[normal] the 
[normal]UK
[normal], so it is not within a jurisdiction 
[normal]in
[normal] which it would be easy for you to find out all the relevant evidence?
[normal] 
[normal]This is a concern about mineral companies where a lot of their activity is not within the 
[normal]UK
[normal] jurisdiction.
[normal] 
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Having a sponsor based in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] actually is of real benefit in that circumstance because, on a day-to-day basis, most of our dialogue in relation to an issuer actually in fact is with the sponsor.
[normal] 
[normal]Having a sponsor firm that has a close relationship with the issuer that it is representing is actually helpful for us in terms of ensuring that the issuer complies with the regime.
[normal] 
[normal]Regarding the financing aspect, which you have talked about, a sponsor does need to be paid somehow, and having the issuer pay for it would be no different from having the issuer pay for the audit.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q151 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Walker:[bold] Can I just ask what legal liability the sponsor has for the veracity of the listing particulars and the details that they publish?
[normal] 
[normal]Are they legally liable for telling the truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: They are certainly liable to us under our regimes.
[normal] 
[normal]In other words, as I was mentioning a few moments ago, if sponsor confirmations turn out to have been inaccurate or produced in a sloppy way, that would bring them under the purview of our discipline.
[normal] 
[normal]I must admit I do not know whether they are able to be pursued through the courts by a third party.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q152 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Walker:[bold] There is also the question not only of accuracy but of inclusivity— including all the facts rather than just stating some which are true.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Yes
[normal].
[normal] The main document that issuers use to come to market is the prospectus.
[normal] 
[normal]The directors of the company take responsibility for the prospectus and they are liable for its contents.
[normal] 
[normal]If there is something that is misleading in a prospectus, then third parties do have the ability to take the directors to court for redress in that respect.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q153 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Mr Lawton, there was an intriguing remark in your written evidence.
[normal] 
[normal]You said, “Our review of an application for listing focuses on ensuring the applicant meets the admission criteria and is therefore eligible for listing.
[normal] 
[normal]We do not consider whether it is suitable for listing.”
[normal] 
[normal]I think most people would find that rather surprising, so why not?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Those two terms are perhaps terms of art in the listing space.
[normal] 
[normal]What I am trying to say there is that the criteria for admission to the List are objective and objectively verifiable.
[normal] 
[normal]What we are not doing is making any comment on a company’s business model.
[normal] 
[normal]For example, if an issuer came to us saying, “We’re a widget
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]maker
[normal],” we make no comments on whether widget
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]making
[normal] is a good business to be in, nor are we making any comment, as we were saying in response to Mr Binley, about whether this is an investment that will make money for investors.
[normal] 
[normal]The focus of our regime is to ensure that issuers make accurate disclosures about themselves in order to enable investors to take a view about whether they want to consider it as an investable proposition.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q154 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] At present, no one actually makes that decision about whether they are suitable for listing in the sense that you have interpreted it.
[normal] 
[normal]You make that decision about eligibility and that is it; once you have done it, they are on the List.
[normal] 
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Yes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q155 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] What checks are you making against what criteria?
[normal] 
[normal]You talked about objective criteria but, in terms of additional information that may be available about a company or allegations that have been made about a company and its practices, which may not strictly fall within a financial prospectus, what other investigations would you normally make?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: The objective criteria are the ones we have touched on a little bit already
[normal], so f
[normal]or a premium listed company, a three
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]year track record, 12 months’ working capital and so on, and appointing a sponsor.
[normal] 
[normal]More broadly, at the point of admission—again this comes back to what we were talking about with Mr
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Binley—we would want to investigate whether a company’s listing, particularly in relation to financial crime, would serve the purpose of 
[normal]us
[normal]ing the 
[normal]UK
[normal] financial system for financial crime.
[normal] 
[normal]That is in our statutory objectives and that does entail us doing some broader analysis of the company.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q156 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Presumably, as you said, you are in close contact with company sponsors.
[normal] 
[normal]If someone made an allegation about a dodgy deal a company may have done a few years ago, for example
[normal],
[normal] presumably you would be in contact with the sponsor about whether or not that allegation could be satisfactorily answered, if it was in the public domain.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: That is typically the sort of detailed conversation we would get into.
[normal] 
[normal]In the context of the structure of our regime, sponsors have a critical role in selecting and promoting, or sponsoring—that is where the word comes from—companies for admission to 
[normal]the List.
[normal] 
[normal]It is clearly an important part of their job and their reputation going forward that they bring companies to the List that they feel comfortable satisfy the criteria.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q157 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Ann [bold]McKechin[bold]:[bold] Just one very quick final question: you mentioned that your new rules allow you to suspend and discipline sponsors of companies have only come into force with effect from this April.
[normal] 
[normal]Does this affect sponsor reports that were submitted prior to that date?
[normal] 
[normal]Does it apply retrospectively or does it only apply to new listings from April?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: It would only apply to sponsor activities since April, yes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q158 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Could you just make clear if there have been any examples where you have said that an applicant company does meet all the criteria from a financial point of view and then the listing authorities turn them down?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: We do have that power in practice.
[normal]Chair:[bold] No, I am asking if it has happened.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: It has happened but, in practice, what tends to happen is that applicants withdraw before we make a final determination.
[normal] 
[normal]When they take a view that we are likely to turn that application down, typically they withdraw their application.
[normal]Chair:[bold] I am talking about you accepting their application or saying that it meets the appropriate criteria, but the 
[normal]UK
[normal] listing authority then deciding to turn it down.
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: In that circumstance, we would say it had not met the criteria, so actually the two questions are the same question.
[normal] 
[normal]Going back to what we talked about, if people are particularly interested, for example, in this concern about financial crime, a statutory objective of ours i
[normal]s
[normal] to protect and enhance the integrity of the 
[normal]UK
[normal] financial system.
[normal] 
[normal]The legislation defines that in part as taking into account the use of the financial system to further financial crime, so that becomes part of our overall assessment.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q159 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I understand that it is normal for a company being listed to have over 25% of its shares available for the open market.
[normal] 
[normal]Now, in some cases, including ENRC, they have been listed without having that requirement.
[normal] 
[normal]Can you explain why an exception was made for companies like this?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: The basic rule is that there need to be sufficient shares in public hands for there to be a liquid secondary market, so that the trading of the shares subsequently works on a satisfactory basis.
[normal] 
[normal]The European listing legislation sets 25% as the basic indicator of sufficient liquidity in the secondary market, but it does give us the ability to have a lower threshold where we are satisfied that there are sufficient shares in public hands for there to be sufficient liquidity.
[normal] 
[normal]In a small number of cases with very large companies, we have assessed that that liquidity criterion would be satisfied with free floats of somewhat less than 25%.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q160 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] The logic of what you have just said would seem to imply that, if a company is of a certain size, there are likely to be enough shares on the free market not to apply that 25% criterion.
[normal] 
[normal]Is that a rough and ready rule?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Yes, but it only happens relatively rarely.
[normal] 
[normal]Another aspect to think about is that, for very large companies coming to market for the first time, there can often be a 
[normal]capacity question.
[normal] 
[normal]The market can only absorb a certain amount of new capital raising at any one point.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q161 [bold]&#xa0; 
