[normal]UK
[normal] is “too liberal about welcoming companies from countries with less transparency” and that you have “too much faith that companies would be transformed through a 
[normal]London
[normal] listing”?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: I would say two things in response to the Professor’s comments.
[normal] 
[normal]The first is that the 
[normal]UK
[normal] regime makes no distinction, in terms of its rules, between companies depending on where they come from.
[normal] 
[normal]In other words, we apply a similar regime to all.
[normal] 
[normal]The premium listing regime has significant standards over and above the European minimum.
[normal] 
[normal]We are already setting standards over and above other European marketplaces.
[normal] 
[normal]Secondly, I would say, and it is plain in relation to the package that we have consulted on in terms of strengthening minority shareholder rights, that there are some areas where the regime does need to be strengthened, taking account of the experience of the last three or four years.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q165 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Do you agree from those comments that you should be tightening up the free float rules?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: The free float is a red herring when it comes to these concerns about shareholder protections, and we have been debating this quite extensively with investors.
[normal] 
[normal]Minority shareholders would be minority shareholders with a free float of 25%, 30% or 40%.
[normal] 
[normal]It is about the protections that they enjoy, whatever the free float, in those circumstances where the controlling shareholder particularly might be taking actions that might be to their disadvantage.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q166 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Caroline [bold]Dinenage[bold]:[bold] Mr Lawton, in your submission you went into some detail about the size of the extractive sector in terms of the companies that are listed in the 
[normal]UK
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Across the board, more and more companies appear to be listing here
[normal].
[normal] Why do you think that is, from the perspective of the listing authority?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Actually, the number of listed companies has been on a slight decline over the last 10
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]years or so, but I think the nature of markets, particularly capital markets, is such that people seek out deep and broad capital markets.
[normal] 
[normal]In particular, companies coming to market are attracted to locations that not only have capital but also have a range of advisory and analytical services to assist them to come to market.
[normal] 
[normal]That has been built up in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] over a long period of time.
[normal] 
[normal]We are clearly not the only financial centre with those sorts of strengths, but they do tend to build on one another over time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q167 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Caroline [bold]Dinenage[bold]:[bold] You talk also in your submission about a “commodities super
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]cycle
[normal]”.
[normal] 
[normal]Can you explain what that concept is, please?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: That just means, if you look over the last 10 years or so, there has been a big upswing in the prices of commodities, so oil, metals and so on, partly related to the growth of emerging markets like 
[normal]China
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]That means that companies in the extractive sector have grown in value.
[normal] 
[normal]As part of that, some of them have wanted to come and tap public capital markets.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q168 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Caroline [bold]Dinenage[bold]:[bold] Obviously many extractive companies are very large and very complex in their structure.
[normal] 
[normal]Can you explain a little bit more about how a company can be listed in more than one country at the same time?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Typically, a company will list in its home market but, if it wants to broaden the base of investors that have an opportunity to invest in it and perhaps seek a larger pool of capital, it might seek to list in another location.
[normal] 
[normal]That is a trend that is less prevalent these days, because it is now a bit easier for investors to invest in markets elsewhere than their home market.
[normal] 
[normal]The number of companies with multiple listings is shrinking, but there is no regulatory barrier to that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q169 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Caroline [bold]Dinenage[bold]:[bold] If a company is listed in several jurisdictions, 
[normal]by
[normal] whose rules do they have to abide?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: They would have to satisfy the capital markets rules in each jurisdiction in which they access capital markets, so all of them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q170 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Caroline [bold]Dinenage[bold]:[bold] If the rules differ or go off in different directions, would they abide differently in different countries?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Yes.
[normal] 
[normal]Typically, the rules would not be conflicting; they would be in layers.
[normal] 
[normal]A company, as a matter of practice, would satisfy the capital markets rules of the most stringent jurisdiction.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q171 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Caroline [bold]Dinenage[bold]:[bold] Quickly, because I know you have already touched on this, could you just outline what the difference is between a primary and a secondary listing, please?
[normal]David Lawton[bold]: Secondary listing was the term that we used to use when companies wanted a second listing, i.e. non
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]UK companies.
[normal] 
[normal]We changed the regime about five years or so ago and opened up that category to 
[normal]UK
[normal] companies and renamed it standard listing.
[normal] 
[normal]A standard listing is one that embodies the European legislative criteria in relation to prospectuses, disclosures and so on.
[normal] 
[normal]A premium listing adds some additional requirements on top of that.
[normal] 
[normal]For the issuer, there is a need to have a three
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]year track record, to be able to say that you have enough working capital to survive at least 12
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]months of activity, and you also have to appoint a sponsor.
[normal] 
[normal]On an ongoing basis, a premium
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]listed
[normal] issuer also has to offer shareholders additional rights to have votes over important transactions such as major acquisitions or transactions with related parties.
[normal]Chair:[bold] Can I bring in Brian Binley now?
[normal]&#xa0;
